Intrduction

This project is meant to analyze the crimes happened in the city Minneapolis, Minnesota using machine learning models, and eventually we will predict crime types with variables that are relevant. In this project, we will be using supervised models to perform classification prediction on our response variable.

The data set is from kaggle.com, it records crimes committed in Minneapolis from 2010 and 2016. The data set contains over 130,000 observations and 35 types of crimes, and also relevant variables like the begin time of the crime, the neighborhood and the crime descriptions. And here is the link to the online data set: crimes data.

The motive of doing the analysis is to see if there are models with relevant predictors to predict where and when will what kind of crime be committed, which will help people live around to protect themselves better and provide insightful information for local police offices to allocate the right amount of police forces at right place and right time.

We can see that there are too many categorical values for Offense and some of them only have a small count. So we are going to combine some of the types of crime according to UCRCode.

Each UCR code represents a larger range of crimes, which can help us combine minority data for better model performance. Here is an example that when UCRCode = 5, we have assault crimes like assault with dangerous weapon and different degrees of domestic assault. We will also be doing the combination with UCRCode = 4 for robbery, UCRCode = 6 for burglary and UCRCode = 8 for vehicle theft.

Set up model

Here we will be starting to build our model.

Trian & test split And K-fold cross validation

For our data set, we are going to split it into training and testing sets with 80% and 20%. Also, we will be doing a 5-fold cross validation.

# splitting into training and testing
crimes_split <- crimes_final %>% initial_split(prop = 0.8, strata = "offense_new")
crimes_train <- training(crimes_split)
crimes_test <- testing(crimes_split)
dim(crimes_train)

# validation set
crimes_valid <- validation_split(crimes_train, prop = 0.75, strata = "offense_new")
crimes_folds <- vfold_cv(crimes_train, v = 5)

Recipe building

Before fitting our data to various models, we are going to build a recipe. Since the rearranged data still having strongly imbalanced observations across values, we are going to upsampling the minority class to 30% of the majority and downsampling the majority to its 80%.

ggplot(data = crimes_train, aes(y = reorder(offense_new, offense_new, length))) +
  geom_histogram(stat = "count") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of training set", y = "Crimes types")

library(themis)

crimes_recipe <- recipe(offense_new ~ hour + x + y, data = crimes_train) %>%
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  step_upsample(offense_new, over_ratio = 0.3, skip = FALSE) %>% 
  step_downsample(offense_new, under_ratio = 0.8, skip = FALSE)

prep(crimes_recipe) %>% 
  bake(new_data = crimes_train) %>% 
  head() %>% 
  kable() %>% 
  kable_styling(full_width = F) %>% 
  scroll_box(width = "100%", height = "200px")

Model building

The models we will be using are K-nearest neighbor, quadratic discriminant analysis, random forest and gradient-boosted trees, where they will make classification predictions if they are fitting well. The process is are: - Setting up models with classification mode and suitable engines; - build up the workflow with models we just created and the recipe; and for K-nearest neighbor, random forest and gradient-boosted trees model, we - set up tuning grid with hyperparameters that we want to tune; - tune the model and choose the best performing model form the tuning grid; then for all four models, we - fit the model to our training set; - save the results to .rda files and load back for analysis. And to make the project file concise, the above process is done in a separate .R file. The metric will be using is the area under ROC curve (roc_auc).

load("C:/Users/Zhengri.DESKTOP-UCNCNBE/Desktop/PSTAT 131/project/knn_tune.rda")

Hyperparameter tuning

For tuning hyperparameters, we will be using the function autoplot() to visualize the tuning grid and see which model perform better with the best hyperparameter value.

K-nearest neighbor model

Here we tuned the number of nearest neighbors (neighbors), where we set the range from 10 to 20 with 10 levels. After loading from the .rda file and do autoplot(), we can see that the roc_auc value with respect to the number of nearest neighbors.

autoplot(knn_tune, metric = "roc_auc") + theme_minimal()

knn_roc <- show_best(knn_tune, n = 1, metric = "roc_auc") %>% 
  select(mean)
best_knn <- select_best(knn_tune, metric = "roc_auc")
best_knn
## # A tibble: 1 × 2
##   neighbors .config              
##       <int> <chr>                
## 1        20 Preprocessor1_Model10

Combined with show_best() function, we get the best number of nearest neighbors is 20. However, the KNN model do not perform well overall with the mean roc_auc value only to increase a little along with increasing of number of nearest neighbors, while the highest value from out tuning grid is only 0.596.

Random forest

Here we tuned the number of predictors at each splitting (mtry), range from 1 to 3, number of trees (trees), range from 200 to 400, and minimum number of data points in a node before splitting (min_n), range from 10 to 20, where the levels are all 5.

autoplot(rf_tune, metric = "roc_auc") + theme_minimal()

rf_roc <- show_best(rf_tune, n = 1, metric = "roc_auc") %>% 
  select(mean)
best_rf <- select_best(rf_tune, metric = "roc_auc")

From above plot, we have a best model with 1 random selected predictors, 300 trees and 20 data points in a node, and the mean roc_auc value has come to 0.62, which shows a better performance.

Gradient-boosted trees

Similar from the random forest, we tuned mtry and trees with same range, and we added learning rate (learn_rate) here, range from -10 to -1.

Find the best model

To choose the best performing model, we need to see how does our QDA model working by fitting to training set.

quad_dis_predict <- predict(quad_dis_fit, new_data = crimes_train)
quad_dis_predict <- bind_cols(quad_dis_predict, crimes_train) %>%
  rename(predicted = .pred_class)
quad_roc <- augment(quad_dis_fit, new_data = quad_dis_predict) %>%
  roc_auc(truth = offense_new,
          .pred_arson, .pred_murder, .pred_sex_crim, .pred_rob, 
          .pred_asslt, .pred_burgl, .pred_thft_gnrl, .pred_thft_othr,
          .pred_thft_vehic) %>% 
  select(.estimate)

Here we have the roc_auc value to be 0.488, which is worse than random guessing. Then from the table below, we can see that the gradient-boosted trees model has the best performance.

roc_value <- c(bt_roc$mean, rf_roc$mean, knn_roc$mean,
               quad_roc$.estimate)
model_name <- c("Gradient-boosted trees", "Random forest",
                "K_nearest neighbors", "Quadratic discriminant analysis")
model_results <- tibble(Model = model_name, ROC_AUC = roc_value)

Conclusion

From the exploration of the raw data, to setting up the model using various resampling methods; by trying on fitting some model, we find that the models would perform no better than random guessing. Besides the trimmed sample size and strongly imbalanced categorical variables, the choice of predictors and model selection are still worth more research on.

When looking at the model performance, we can see that the simpler models like QDA and KNN has performance not as good as random forest and gradient-boosted trees in terms of predicting response that has large amount of categorical values. In that case, we may expect considering more predictors or more focused predictions like whether someone will commit certain crime at certain time and location.

Overall, we have investigated and learned a lot from the whole process, and predicting classification models indeed need more adjusting and tuning to deal with complicated problems like crimes. In conclusion, data analysis and machine learning techniques are powerful and we have more to learn to effectively utilized them.
